to prick your finger,

00:40:15.520 --> 00:40:17.800
and put it on a
little piece of paper,

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:21.670
and stick it in the machine,
and see what the number is.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:25.600
So some way-- and I've worked
with some companies that

00:40:25.600 --> 00:40:30.340
are using light technology to
perhaps look at the wavelengths

00:40:30.340 --> 00:40:35.050
on hemoglobin to see what the
glycosylation of the hemoglobin

00:40:35.050 --> 00:40:39.190
is to detect the glucose levels.

00:40:39.190 --> 00:40:41.950
So noninvasive glucose
monitoring as well as

00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:43.780
continuous glucose monitoring.

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:48.370
So my patients are
so surprised by when

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:50.800
they eat, if they
prick their finger,

00:40:50.800 --> 00:40:52.030
their glucose is higher.

00:40:52.030 --> 00:40:53.987
And sort of really
connecting what

00:40:53.987 --> 00:40:55.570
you're putting in
your body and what's

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:56.950
happening to your glucose.

00:40:56.950 --> 00:41:02.710
And what is happening long term
to your heart disease risk is,

00:41:02.710 --> 00:41:03.944
I think--

00:41:03.944 --> 00:41:06.110
would be great to connect
the dots for our patients.

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:16.860
AUDIENCE: I think
